{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20906"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20906"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96965"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13781"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79580"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10740"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"12380"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96965"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents with primary amenorrhoea and short stature. On examination, she is 145 cm tall with a webbed neck, widely spaced nipples, and underdeveloped secondary sexual characteristics. Pelvic ultrasound reveals streak ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the chromosomal abnormality most frequently associated with this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Partial deletion of the X chromosome short arm","Complete monosomy of the X chromosome","Isochromosome formation of the X chromosome long arm","Mosaic pattern with 45,X/46,XX cells","Y chromosome material translocation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is typical of Turner syndrome, with characteristic features including short stature, primary amenorrhoea, webbed neck, and streak ovaries. The most common chromosomal finding in this condition is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete monosomy of the X chromosome\u003C/strong\u003E, resulting in a 45,X karyotype, which accounts for approximately 57% of Turner syndrome cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe alternative chromosomal patterns listed are less frequently observed in Turner syndrome:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial deletion of the X chromosome short arm\u003C/strong\u003E represents one of several possible structural abnormalities in Turner syndrome but occurs less commonly than complete X monosomy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsochromosome formation of the X chromosome long arm\u003C/strong\u003E (46,X,i(X)(q10)) is the most prevalent structural abnormality in Turner syndrome but still represents only a minority of cases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMosaic pattern with 45,X/46,XX cells\u003C/strong\u003E is found in roughly 29% of Turner syndrome cases. Patients with mosaicism typically exhibit milder clinical manifestations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EY chromosome material translocation\u003C/strong\u003E is present in only 5-10% of Turner syndrome patients and carries an elevated risk of gonadoblastoma development.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETurner syndrome results from complete or partial X chromosome monosomy. The SHOX gene, located in the pseudoautosomal region of the X chromosome, plays a crucial role in the pathogenesis of short stature in this condition. Typically, both males and females possess two functional copies of this gene. In Turner syndrome, having only one copy of SHOX (haploinsufficiency) contributes to the characteristic short stature. Other clinical features such as cardiovascular abnormalities (present in 25-50% of patients) and ovarian dysgenesis result from the loss of additional X chromosome genes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Turner syndrome is characterized by complete or partial absence of one X chromosome, occurring in approximately 1 in 2000 female births.","The predominant karyotype in Turner syndrome is 45,X (about 57%), with other cases showing structural X chromosome abnormalities (14%) or mosaicism (29%).","Haploinsufficiency of the SHOX gene contributes significantly to the short stature seen in Turner syndrome."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 171-173"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79580"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20906"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79580"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T22:47:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T22:48:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13781"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96965"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10738"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chromosomal disorders